Anonymous Class in Java

An anonymous class is a class without a name that is created and used in one place.

👉 It is used when you need a quick implementation of a class or interface.

Basic Idea

Instead of creating a separate class, you define it inline.

Example with Interface
Runnable r = new Runnable() {
    @Override
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Running...");
    }
};

👉 No class name — created on the spot

Example with Class
class Animal {
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Animal sound");
    }
}

Animal a = new Animal() {
    @Override
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }
};
Key Features
no class name
used once
defined and instantiated at the same time
can extend a class or implement an interface
When to use Anonymous Class

Use it when:

implementation is small
needed only in one place
you want quick and simple code
Limitations
cannot have constructors
harder to read if too big
cannot be reused
Anonymous Class vs Lambda
Anonymous Class	Lambda
works with class or interface	works only with functional interface
more verbose	shorter
can have multiple methods	only one method
Example with Lambda (modern way)
Runnable r = () -> System.out.println("Running...");

👉 Cleaner and preferred in modern Java

Summary
anonymous class = class without name
used for quick one-time implementation
can extend class or implement interface
often replaced by lambda in modern Java
